findings.remediation:
Add a Zod validation schema for the update endpoint that only allows `name` and `email` fields:

```typescript
// auth.schemas.ts or user.schemas.ts
export const updateMeSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1).max(100).optional(),
  email: z.string().email().optional(),
});
```

Apply the validation middleware on the route:

```typescript
// user.routes.ts
router.patch('/me', validate({ body: updateMeSchema }), updateMe);
```

Alternatively, use an explicit allowlist in the service layer:

```typescript
const { name, email } = data;
const sanitized = { ...(name && { name }), ...(email && { email }) };
const user = await User.findByIdAndUpdate(id, sanitized, { new: true, runValidators: true });
```

1. Remove the default fallback for JWT_SECRET in docker-compose.yml — require it to be explicitly set:

```yaml
JWT_SECRET: ${JWT_SECRET:?JWT_SECRET must be set}
```

2. Add a runtime check in `env.ts` that rejects known insecure defaults when `NODE_ENV=production`:

```typescript
const KNOWN_INSECURE_SECRETS = [
  'change-me-to-a-secure-random-string',
  'change-me-to-a-secure-random-string-at-least-32-chars',
];

if (result.data.NODE_ENV === 'production' &&
    KNOWN_INSECURE_SECRETS.some(s => result.data.JWT_SECRET.includes(s))) {
  throw new Error('JWT_SECRET must not use a default/example value in production');
}
```

3. Specify the allowed algorithm in `jwt.verify`: `jwt.verify(token, env.JWT_SECRET, { algorithms: ['HS256'] })`
